{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:51:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:51:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14363"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14363","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14363"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.57,0.06,0.03,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7058"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59663"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7058"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14363"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45075"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"2248"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16818"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59663"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA junior doctor on a night shift in a metropolitan emergency department has been allocated to the short stay unit overnight. Shortly after the start of their shift, a nurse approaches them with an arterial blood gas (ABG) result for a patient they were handed over. They can remember that the patient is a 65-year-old woman who initially presented with new confusion on the background of a recent lower limb fracture. The ABG had been ordered as the patient had started to desaturate in their sleep. The ABG has now revealed a PaO2 of 55 mmHg (75-100), PaCO2 of 35 mmHg (35-45), and pH of 7.45 (7.35-7.45).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"On the basis of this blood gas result alone, which of the following is the most likely diagnosis for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Opiate toxicity","Pulmonary embolism","Obesity hypoventilation syndrome","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","Obstructive sleep apnoea"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe arterial blood gas results show isolated hypoxia with a normal carbon dioxide level, indicating type one respiratory failure. This pattern is typically seen in conditions that cause a ventilation-perfusion mismatch, such as a \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary embolism\u003C/strong\u003E. A pulmonary embolism can lead to areas of the lung being ventilated but not perfused, resulting in hypoxaemia without hypercapnia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are all examples of type 2 respiratory failure - characterised by alveolar hypoventilation and characteristically elevated CO2 (hypercapnia) in addition to hypoxia. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)\u003C/strong\u003E often leads to type two respiratory failure, with both hypoxia and hypercapnia due to impaired ventilation in the presence of airway obstruction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpiate toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes type two respiratory failure due to respiratory depression and oversedation, leading to hypoventilation. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive sleep apnoea (OSA)\u003C/strong\u003E can cause intermittent hypoxia during sleep. It is not, however, associated with isolated hypoxia on an arterial blood gas - as another example of alveolar hypoventilation and type the expected changes would also include an elevated CO2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity hypoventilation syndrome (OHS)\u003C/strong\u003E is also associated with type two respiratory failure due to hypoventilation, leading to elevated carbon dioxide levels along with hypoxia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Isolated hypoxia with normal or low carbon dioxide levels on arterial blood gas is indicative of type one respiratory failure.","Pulmonary embolism is a common cause of type one respiratory failure due to ventilation-perfusion mismatch.","Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, opiate toxicity, obstructive sleep apnoea, and obesity hypoventilation syndrome typically cause type two respiratory failure."],"references":["Mirabile VS, Shebl E, Sankari A, Burns B. Respiratory Failure in Adults. 2023 Jun 11. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30252383. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30252383/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45075"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14363"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45075"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T15:27:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T15:27:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7058"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59663"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app